## Step 4 — Check Buffer Cache Health

High physical reads often mean data is not being cached. Check memory health:

```sql
SELECT 
    counter_name,
    cntr_value
FROM sys.dm_os_performance_counters
WHERE counter_name IN (
    'Buffer cache hit ratio',
    'Page life expectancy',
    'Page reads/sec',
    'Lazy writes/sec'
);
```

**Healthy values:**

| Metric | Healthy | Problem |
|---|---|---|
| Buffer cache hit ratio | > 95% | < 90% = too many disk reads |
| Page life expectancy | > 300 sec | < 300 = data evicted from memory too fast |
| Page reads/sec | < 90 | > 90 = heavy disk reads happening |
| Lazy writes/sec | ~0 | High = severe memory pressure |

