## Step 9 — Infrastructure Fixes (Azure SQL VM)

If disk stall confirmed > 30ms in Step 3, address the storage layer:

### 9.1 — Upgrade Disk Type in Azure Portal

```
Azure Portal → Virtual Machine → Disks → Click Data Disk → Change Type
```

| Disk Type | Avg Latency | Recommendation |
|---|---|---|
| Standard HDD | 10 – 50ms | ❌ Not suitable for SQL Server |
| Standard SSD | 5 – 15ms | ⚠️ Dev/Test only |
| Premium SSD | 1 – 5ms | ✅ Recommended for production |
| Ultra Disk | < 1ms | ✅ Best for high IOPS workloads |

### 9.2 — Enable Read Caching on Data Disk

```
Azure Portal → VM → Disks → Data Disk → Host Caching → Read-only
```

> ⚠️ Set log file disk caching to **None** — log writes must always go directly to disk for durability.

### 9.3 — Best Practice Disk Layout for SQL VM

```
C:\  →  OS only
D:\  →  SQL Data files (.mdf, .ndf)   [ Premium SSD | Cache: Read-only ]
E:\  →  SQL Log files  (.ldf)         [ Premium SSD | Cache: None      ]
F:\  →  TempDB                        [ Local SSD or Premium SSD       ]
G:\  →  Backups                       [ Standard SSD (cost saving OK)  ]
```

### 9.4 — Increase SQL Server Max Memory

More RAM = more data cached in buffer pool = fewer disk reads:

```sql
-- Check current memory settings
SELECT 
    physical_memory_in_use_kb / 1024    AS memory_used_mb,
    page_fault_count
FROM sys.dm_os_process_memory;

-- Set max server memory (leave ~10% for OS)
-- Example: 16GB RAM server → set to 14336 MB
EXEC sp_configure 'max server memory (MB)', 14336;
RECONFIGURE;
```

---

## Step 10 — Verify Fix is Working

After applying fixes, run this to confirm IO_COMPLETION waits have reduced:

```sql
-- Clear wait stats (do this BEFORE applying fix, then check again after)
-- WARNING: This resets all historical wait stats
DBCC SQLPERF ('sys.dm_os_wait_stats', CLEAR);

-- Then after 30 minutes of normal workload, re-run:
SELECT 
    wait_type,
    waiting_tasks_count,
    wait_time_ms / 1000.0  AS total_wait_secs,
    wait_time_ms * 100.0 /
    SUM(wait_time_ms) OVER() AS pct_of_total
FROM sys.dm_os_wait_stats
WHERE wait_type = 'IO_COMPLETION'
ORDER BY wait_time_ms DESC;
```

**Success criteria:** IO_COMPLETION drops below 5% of total wait time.

